      "id": "d3f6e9855f22b121",
      "text": "I followed a process of inquiry developed by Laszlo & Krippner (1998), which builds systems theory into the traditional scientific method of analysis. I investigated the concept of ‘Boundary’ across the transdisciplinary literatures of technology, innovation and leadership, looking for patterns and areas of overlap in order to deconstruct ‘the Boundary’ and describe its components; formulate explanations that account for the behaviour or properties of boundary components taken separately; synthesize these explanations into an aggregate understanding of the whole; then synthesize through the lens of systems theory (Figure 1)."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "b6f1dc813bee6371",
      "text": "I present the research findings about Boundary within and without the systems thinking/science discipline, its relationship to technology, networks, knowledge creation and management, innovation and leadership, and identify generalizable characteristics and understandings of ‘Boundary’ in order to understand the nature of ‘Boundary’ – it’s being. In the spirit of the founding fathers of systems science, the aim is to develop a meta-level theory and model ”applicable to more than one of the traditional departments of knowledge” (Checkland, 1999, p. 59)."
